{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}} {{Use Irish English|date=January 2014}} {{Infobox University |name =IBAT College Dublin |former_names = {{Plainlist| *Institute of Business and Technology *IBAT College Swords }} |image = IBAT College Dublin - logo 2018.jpg |type = Private, [[for-profit education|for-profit]] higher education institution |established =2004 |founder = Shane Ormsby |director = Shane Ormsby |students = {{circa}}1500 (as of 2017)<ref name ="ST" /> | free_label = Owner | free = [[Global University Systems]] |address = 16-19 Wellington Quay |city =[[Dublin]] |country =[[Republic of Ireland]] |website ={{URL|ibat.ie}} }}
'''IBAT College Dublin''' is a private [[for-profit education|for-profit]] higher education institution located in [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland]]. It was founded in 2004 as the '''Institute of Business and Technology'''. From 2009 to 2011 it was known as '''IBAT College Swords'''. As of 2018, the college offers two part-time Bachelor of Arts degrees and an [[MBA]], all of which are validated by the [[University of Wales Trinity Saint David]]. It also offers English-language courses and its own short courses in various subjects related to business and technology.
==History== The college was founded in 2004 by Shane Ormsby who was its director and principal shareholder. Originally called the Institute of Business and Technology, its first campus was on Forster Way in the [[Swords, Dublin|Swords]] area of north Dublin. In 2006, it received programme validation from the [[Higher Education and Training Awards Council]] (HETAC). By 2011, it was offering the Certificate in Business, Higher Certificate in Business, Bachelor of Business, and Bachelor of Business (Honours). In addition to those HETAC validated programmes, it also offered an [[MBA]] validated by the [[University of Wales Trinity Saint David]] and various accountancy, business, and technology training programmes which at the time were approved by [[Accounting Technicians Ireland|ATI]], [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants|ACCA]], [[Irish Computer Society|ICS]] and [[Institute of Commercial Management|ICM]].<ref name="HETAC">[[HETAC]] (2012). [https://www.qqi.ie/Publications/Publications/IBAT%20College%20Dublin,%20Institutional%20Review%20-%20April%202012,%20Terms%20of%20Reference.pdf ''Institutional Review of IBAT College Dublin'']. Retrieved 27 July 2018</ref><ref name= "QQI">[[Quality and Qualifications Ireland]] (January 2017). [https://www.qqi.ie/Publications/Publications/FINAL%20Report%20of%20Review%20of%20Validated%20Programmes%20at%20IBAT%20College%20Jan%202017.pdf ''Final Report: Review of Validated Programmes offered by IBAT College under Section 46 of the Qualifications and Quality Assurance (Education and Training) Act, 2012'']. Retrieved 27 July 2018.</ref>
The College had changed its name from the Institute of Business and Technology to IBAT College Swords in July 2009. It was changed again in July 2011 to its present name, IBAT College Dublin. The 2011 name change reflected IBAT's move to a new purpose-built main campus in the center of Dublin at [[Temple Bar, Dublin|Temple Bar]].<ref name="HETAC" /> In 2014 the college entered into an agreement with [[Global University Systems]] (GUS) which involved GUS assisting IBAT with student recruitment and marketing. The GUS subsidiary Interactive would also digitise the learning materials for the college's ACCA accountancy courses. At that time Ormsby said that there had been no discussions about the company taking a financial stake in his business.<ref>Lyons, Tom (23 December 2014). [http://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/ibat-college-in-deal-with-private-education-provider-global-university-systems-1.2046964 "Ibat college in deal with private education provider Global University Systems"]. ''[[The Irish Times]]''. Retrieved 27 July 2018.</ref>
From the outset, the college has catered mainly to students from outside Ireland, the majority of whom are also from outside the [[European Economic Area]]. Concerns about the college's acceptance of students without the requisite level of English for higher education study, poor student progression and retention rates, and lax admissions procedures and record-keeping led to a review by [[Quality and Qualifications Ireland]] (QQI) which was completed in January 2017. At the conclusion of the review, validation was removed from all of the college's HETAC business programmes. Despite the withdrawal of accreditation for its HETAC business courses, IBAT was still allowed to recruit non-EU students on visas for its English-language courses. Its MBA validated by the University of Wales remained unaffected.<ref name= "QQI" /><ref name ="ST">Tighe, Mark (15 October 2017), [https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/college-gets-marked-down-bb0nr3hrk "College gets marked down"]. ''[[The Sunday Times]]''. Retrieved 27 July 2018 (subscription required for full access).</ref><ref name ="QAA">[[QAA]] (October 2017). [http://www.qaa.ac.uk/docs/qaa/international/tne-ireland-university-of-wales-trinity-saint-davies.pdf?sfvrsn=a11af481_2 ''Review of UK transnational education in the Republic of Ireland: University of Wales Trinity Saint David and IBAT College'']. Retrieved 27 July 2018.</ref>
In November 2016, as the QQI review was taking place, IBAT Dublin was sold to Global University Systems. Shane Ormsby remained the college's director after the takeover.<ref name ="ST" />
==Academic programmes== As of 2018, IBAT Dublin offers two part-time Bachelor of Arts (Honours) degrees in Sports Management and Development and in International Business. It also offers an [[MBA]] which can be studied full- or part-time. All three degrees are validated by the [[University of Wales Trinity Saint David]]. In addition to the degree programes, IBAT offers English-language courses and its own short courses in various subjects related to business and technology.<ref>IBAT College Dublin. [https://www.ibat.ie/undergraduate-full-time-courses-dublin.html Undergraduate Courses]; [https://www.ibat.ie/masters-postgraduate-courses.html Postgraduate Courses]; [https://www.ibat.ie/part-time-evening-courses-dublin.html Short/Evening Courses]; [https://www.ibat.ie/english-language-school-dublin-courses.html English Language School]. Retrieved 27 July 2018.</ref>
